    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i've also heard some people say that originalism is basically just a way for judges to push a specific political agenda while pretending to be neutral. do you think those criticisms are valid, or is that just a misunderstanding of the theory?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The criticism that originalism is a mask for judicial activism is a common and significant counterargument. Critics argue that pinpointing a single \"original public meaning\" is inherently subjective and often requires significant interpretive choices. They suggest that what proponents call \"originalism\" can easily become a vehicle for embedding the philosophies of the justices interpreting the text today. Therefore, whether the criticism is valid often depends on how strictly one defines the methodology in practice.",
      "source": "target",
