      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is a valid observation that originalist arguments are frequently employed in cases concerning social policy and civil liberties. Critics contend that when the goal is consistently to restrict established rights, the methodology devolves into advocacy rather than objective interpretation. From this perspective, if the primary function becomes achieving partisan outcomes rather than discovering enduring constitutional principles, its legitimacy is severely undermined. This tension between theory and contemporary application remains a major point of legal debate.",
      "source": "target",
